First off, I don't think it's necessary. BUT, having some sort of set process will really save a lot of time and trouble. I usually ask the client to send me anything they think I need to know, then I basically start arranging info and fill the gaps from there.

With content and web work, there's generally a lot of material to get through (get to know the brand, voice, tone, products, SMEs, etc). Sometimes hard to tell what's missing!

text:
Hi all, Question for anyone that pays freelancers in other currencies...

I'm in Australia and have started working with a writer in the UK. She's new to this arrangement and so am I - she suggested I pay her via paypal but it seems there's a big chunk of change taken out in fees.

I tried to make the payment a few different ways but one of us has to cop the fee. Is there a way around this for someone like me who only has a very low requirement for paying OS contractors?  I know there's some big platforms for managing many international staff but for us it will be literally < $300 per month so not worth forking out for a subscription solution.

Our agreement specifically excludes tax and things like that so that isn't a factor. Any ideas how to manage this better?
